ne, Île-de-France, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"abt 1104–":"about 1104–Deceased","1104–Female":"1104–Deceased","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","–Unknown":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1057–Male":"1057–Deceased","abt 1104":"about 1104","1104":"1104","7 January 1121":"7 January 1121","1057":"1057","1101":"1101","1121":"1121","1182":"1182","Chateau-Landon, Gatinais, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"CHATEAU","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Thierry, Francois, Michel.","French (<b>Château</b>):","from Old French <i>chastel</i> (French <i>château</i>) ‘castle, fortified building’, a topographic name for someone who lived in or near a castle, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked in one."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celine, Emile, Gilles, Jacques, Lucien.","French (also <b>Châtel</b>):","habitational name from (Le) Chatel or (Le) Châtel, names of several places in various parts of France, from Old French <i>chastel</i> ‘castle, fortified building’."]},{"name":"Duchateau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Andree, Armand, Philippe.","French (<b>Duchâteau</b>); Walloon and Flemish (rarely <b>Duchâteau</b>): topographic name, with fused French preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’, from Old French <i>chastel</i> (French <i>château</i>) ‘castle, fortified building’ (see   Chateau  ), or a habitational name denoting someone from Le Château, the name of several places in various parts of France and in Belgium (Wallonia) named with <i>château</i>."]}]},{"name":"LANDON","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: altered form of   Langdon  .","English: habitational name from Lavendon (Buckinghamshire), which is recorded as <i>Laundone</i> in 1232 and <i>Lavenden alias Launden</i> in 1639. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Lāfa</i> (genitive <i>Lāfan</i>) + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Lando</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’, via the oblique case, <i>Landonis</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Langdon","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places, for example in Devon, Dorset, Essex, Kent, and Warwickshire, so named from Old English <i>lang</i>, <i>long</i> ‘long’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. See also   Longden  .","History: Samuel Langdon, Harvard College president in 1774–80, was born in Boston, MA, in 1723 but lived out his years in Hampton Falls, NH. Three of his children left descendants. His grandfather Philip (born 1646) had came from Braunton in Devon, England, and was married in Andover, Essex County, MA, in 1684. Another early Langdon immigrant was Tobias Langdon, who came to North America before 1660 and settled in Portsmouth, NH. His great-grandson John was a revolutionary war leader, US senator, and NH governor."]}]},{"name":"Beline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":[", also found in the English-speaking world: apparently from Latin <i>Caelina</i>, a feminine form of <i>Caelinus</i>, which is a derivative of <i>Caelius</i> (  see  Celia  ). It may alternatively be a short form of Marcelline ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Beline DE CHATEAU LANDON was born about 1104, in France as the daughter of Dimon de Château-Landon. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Lord Robert I d'Nemours Clement Lord."},"et":{"abt 1104–":"umbes 1104–Surnud","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","–Unknown":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1057–Male":"1057–Surnud","abt 1104":"umbes 1104","1104":"1104","7 January 1121":"7. jaanuar 1121","1057":"1057","1101":"1101","1121":"1121","1182":"1182","Chateau-Landon, Gatinais, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"abt 1104–":"noin 1104–Kuollut","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","–Unknown":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1057–Male":"1057–Kuollut","abt 1104":"noin 1104","1104":"1104","7 January 1121":"7. tammikuuta 1121","1057":"1057","1101":"1101","1121":"1121","1182":"1182","Chateau-Landon, Gatinais, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"abt 1104–":"environ 1104–Décédée","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","1101–1182":"1101–1182","1121–1182":"1121–1182","–Unknown":"Décédé(e)","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1057–Male":"1057–Décédé","abt 1104":"environ 1104","1104":"1104","7 January 1121":"7 janvier 1121","1057":"1057","1101":"1101","1121":"1121","1182":"1182","Chateau-Landon, Gatinais, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Beline DE CHATEAU LANDON est née environ 1104, à France, fille de Dimon de Château-Landon. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils et 1 fille avec Lord Robert I d'Ne